# Salesforce: system of record for customers

**Salesforce** is the **ultimate system of record** for **who is a customer** and **customer status** (active installed base vs churned / inactive contract, ARR, renewal dates). **Pendo**, **Jira/Atlassian**, CS Report, LeanDNA, and other integrations supply **enrichment only**—they must **never** be treated as authoritative for customer inventory or churn/active classification.

## Customer inventory (who is in the book)

- Use Salesforce `Account` records with `Type = 'Customer Entity'` (`SalesforceClient.get_entity_accounts()` and related helpers) as the source of truth for which customers belong in the portfolio / book of business—not raw Pendo sitename-prefix enumeration.
- Portfolio enumeration follows `BPO_PORTFOLIO_CUSTOMER_SOURCE` and `src/portfolio_salesforce_allowlist.py` / `PendoClient.get_portfolio_report`. Prefer extending that model over re-deriving the customer set from Pendo alone unless product explicitly requires Pendo-only discovery.
- YAML maps (e.g. `customer_identity_map.yaml`, `cohorts.yaml`) are **adjuncts** for aliases and presentation—they do not override Salesforce.

## Customer status (active vs churned)

- **Active / churned / contract health** come from Salesforce contract rollups and entity metrics—not from Pendo login trends, Jira ticket volume, or CS Report alone.
- Do **not** classify a customer as churned or active based only on Pendo absence, low usage, or Jira/Atlassian signals. Those may inform narrative; **Salesforce contract status decides**.
- When joining SF to other systems, **warn** (do not silently skip) when there is no matching Pendo prefix or when SF labels are unmatched—preserve that pattern for new features.

## When Salesforce is missing or unavailable

| Situation | Expected behavior |
|-----------|-------------------|
| SF **configured**, API/query **fails** | **Fail loud** (see `fail-loud-integrations.mdc`): surface the error in export/deck coverage; do **not** infer churn or customer set from Pendo/Jira instead. |
| SF **not configured**, `BPO_PORTFOLIO_CUSTOMER_SOURCE=auto` | Pendo sitename prefixes may enumerate the book—an **explicit env fallback**, not a second system of record. Do not treat that mode as CRM-backed churn classification. |
| SF **configured**, customer has **no Pendo prefix** | Keep the Salesforce row and facts; Pendo enrichment is optional. **Warn** on the join miss. |
| Account **not** a Salesforce Customer Entity | Outside CRM-backed portfolio scope unless product defines a separate, documented non-SF path. |

## Data freshness

- Salesforce reads may be served from in-process cache (`BPO_SALESFORCE_CACHE_TTL_HOURS`, default 48h). Stale CRM data can produce confidently wrong churn or ARR.
- In user-facing exports and coverage manifests, **state whether Salesforce loaded successfully** and, when feasible, **how fresh the data is** (pull time, cache TTL, or “cached as of …”) so readers do not treat an old snapshot as live CRM.

## Exports and decks

- **Active installed base** and **churned / inactive contract** customers belong in **separate presentation paths**: active rows may include Pendo, Jira, and other enrichment; the churn segment is **Salesforce-only** (no Pendo or Jira slices mixed in as if they were still in the active book).
- Do **not** merge churned Salesforce accounts back into active portfolio tables or allowlists used for usage and support narrative.
- Deck slides and portfolio views should label or filter churn using **Salesforce-backed fields** when CRM data is loaded; when CRM is not loaded, say so—do not imply Salesforce-confirmed status.

## Anti-patterns (avoid)

- Building an allowlist or “customers to include” from Pendo `customer_list` alone when Salesforce is configured.
- Dropping SF customers because Pendo has no prefix match (include SF facts; Pendo is optional).
- Using Jira organization names or Pendo sitenames as the canonical customer key without mapping through Salesforce labels / `portfolio_salesforce_allowlist`.
- Silently substituting Pendo or Jira signals when Salesforce fails or is stale.
